title: For Sale:  Vetterli-Vitali M1870/87/15
postcontent: Here is a nice example of an Italian Vetterli-Vitali M1870/87/15 rifle in 6.5 Carcano. This one was made in 1881 in Torino. It is all original. This rifle began life as a Model 1870 single shot rifle, was arsenal converted to a magazine fed repeater in 1887 and then again arsenal modified to fire 6.5 Carcano for use by 2nd line troops in WWI in 1915. The bore is in great condition and the rifle is functional. The gun is in arsenal-stored condition and needs to be oiled and the traces of cosmoline cleaned. Includes rifle, one enbloc magazine, 6 rounds of 6.5 Carcano and sling. While fully functional, this gun was never intended to fire modern smokeless powder 6.5 Carcano except in a last-ditch emergency situation i.e. World War I. While it will handle it, it is not recommended. 6.5 Carcano rounds loaded with black powder are what you want to shoot in it *IF* you decide to shoot it at all. The 6 included rounds are modern smokeless 6.5 Carcano that would probably be a bad idea to shoot out of it. You could pull the bullets and save the brass.

title: For Sale:  M1892 revolver
postcontent: Here is an interesting M1892 “Lebel” double-action revolver in its original 8mm chambering manufactured in 1893. It is not import marked and my understanding is that this was a WWII bring-back. The grips are obviously not original, in fact, upon closer inspection you will notice that they were hand fashioned from the unmistakeable wood of a K98 German Mauser buttstock. The bottom of the grip frame is sheared off where the grip plate and lanyard ring were. It’s unclear if this was done intentionally to accommodate the grips, or if the grips were designed as a repair for a damaged grip frame which would have prevented the original grips from staying on properly. I’d like to think this is a French Resistance gun that was modified with on-hand materials, but who knows.
